  "business_context": "Engagement records hold the structure of relationships that span multiple interactions over time. They differ from Activity (which captures a single call, meeting, or task) and from Case (which is more problem-oriented with a defined resolution): Engagement is about a sustained relationship that has goals, stages, and outcomes. The CBM pilot client uses Engagement as the central entity for mentor-mentee relationships, where a single engagement spans months of touchpoints across mentoring sessions, check-ins, and program milestones. Salesforce NPSP has the Engagement Plan / Engagement Plan Task / Engagement Plan Template trio, used for structured donor-cultivation tracks. CiviCRM has Cases that can serve a similar long-running role (Case management for human-services contexts). Bloomerang doesn't have a first-class Engagement entity — relationships are tracked via Interactions accumulated against a Constituent. The B2B systems generally don't have a long-running engagement concept beyond Opportunity (which is revenue-focused). When interviewing clients, surface \"Engagement\" by asking whether they need to track relationships that span many interactions over months or years (mentor-mentee, donor-cultivation, beneficiary-services, advocacy-coalition), and whether those relationships have their own lifecycle stages (recruited, matched, active, completed, paused).",
